\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Inference for agreement coefficients with missing ratings using pairwise complete data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Missing data is a pervasive challenge in studies of interrater agreement,
 yet common agreement coefficients—
such as Conger’s kappa,
 Fleiss’ kappa (and Krippendorff’s alpha),
 and the Brennan–Prediger coefficient—
are often applied without clear justification when ratings are incomplete.
 We develop a general framework for handling missing data in agreement analysis that supports both categorical and continuous responses,
 allows arbitrary disagreement functions,
 and holds provided the data is pairwise missing completely at random.
 We characterize when pairwise-available estimators remain consistent,
 derive their correct standard errors,
 and identify settings where conventional formulas fail.
 We then propose reweighted kappa estimators that remain valid under substantially weaker assumptions.
 Asymptotic covariance matrices enable joint inference across coefficients,
 and simulations verify the theoretical claims.
 The methods are implemented in an R package 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{misskappa}$
\end_inset

 designed for applied use.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Jonas Moss,
 Rutger van Oest
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A chance-corrected agreement coefficient is any coefficient on the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{x}=1-\frac{d}{d_{x}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is a measure of disagreement and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{x}$
\end_inset

 a measure of chance disagreement.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $l(x,y)\geq0$
\end_inset

 be a symmetric loss function satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $l(x,x)=0$
\end_inset

.
 The most common are nominal 
\begin_inset Formula $l(x,y)=1[x\neq y]$
\end_inset

,
 absolute value (or linear) 
\begin_inset Formula $l(x,y)=|x-y|$
\end_inset

,
 and quadratic 
\begin_inset Formula $l(x,y)=(x-y)^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 For categorical responses, let
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 be the category set with
\begin_inset Formula $|\mathcal{C}|=C$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a random vector with 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 components.
 Define disagreement as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d=\binom{R}{2}^{-1}\sum_{j<k}E[l(X_{j}^{\star},X_{k}^{\star})].\label{eq:population disagreement}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We cover three variants of chance disagreement,
 the Fleiss-type,
 Cohen-type,
 and Brennan–Prediger-type.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
d_{F} & = & R^{-2}\sum_{j,k}E[l(X_{ij}^{\star},X_{i'k}^{\star})],\label{eq:fleiss disagreement}\\
d_{C} & = & \binom{R}{2}^{-1}\sum_{j<k}E[l(X_{ij}^{\star},X_{i'k}^{\star})],\label{eq:cohendisagreement}\\
d_{BP} & = & C^{-2}\sum_{x\in\mathcal{C}}\sum_{y\in\mathcal{C}}l(x,y).\label{eq:bp disagreement}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Interpretations can be found in the agreement-coefficient literature; here we only use the loss-based representation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For complete data the kappa coefficients are estimated using the natural sample counterparts.
 Their standard errors may be found using either multinomial theory or 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistics.
  
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Available-case estimator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The available case estimator is a popular estimator of kappa coefficients with missing data.
 It is the default estimator in the R package irrCAC when the data contains missing values.
 If we let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}^{\star}$
\end_inset

 be the complete observations and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{ij}$
\end_inset

 the missingness indicators for the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

th rater,
 we may define the available case Conger's kappa estimator as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{C}^{AC}=1-\hat{d}^{AC}/\hat{d}_{C}^{AC}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{d}^{AC} & = & \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{j<k}l(X_{ij}^{\star},X_{ik}^{\star})M_{ij}M_{ik}}{\sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{j<k}M_{ij}M_{ik}},\quad\hat{d}_{C}^{AC}=\frac{\sum_{i,i'}\sum_{j<k}l(X_{ij}^{\star},X_{i'k}^{\star})M_{ij}M_{i'k}}{\sum_{i,i'}\sum_{j<k}M_{ij}M_{i'k}}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The available case estimators of Fleiss' kappa and the Brennan–Prediger coefficient are defined in the same way.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The estimator has been studied,
 using simulation studies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Warrens2025-gt"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for two raters and quadratic weights.
 Our first goal is to find 
\emph on
reasonable 
\emph default
miminal conditions for when the estimator is consistent.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Conditions for consistency
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:missingness"

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\star}$
\end_inset

 be a random vector of size 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be the observed incomplete data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The components of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are missing 
\emph on
uniformly at random
\emph default
 if the component-wise missingness probabilities are constant (i.e.,
 
\begin_inset Formula $P(M_{i})=\pi$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{j}$
\end_inset

 are independent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{I}(x^{\star})=P\left(\bigcap_{i\in I}\{M_{i}=1\}\mid x^{\star}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The components of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are missing 
\emph on
pairwise completely at random
\emph default
 (PMCAR) if 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{I}(x^{\star})$
\end_inset

 is constant in 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\star}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $|I|\leq2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Definition
Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is MCAR implies PMCAR.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is MCAR iff 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{I}(x^{\star})$
\end_inset

 is constant in 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\star}$
\end_inset

 for any pattern 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq\{1,\ldots,R\}$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand,
 PMCAR does not imply MCAR,
 it does not even imply MAR!
 That said,
 MAR mechanisms that are not MCAR will typically not be MCAR [[investigate]].
\end_layout

