Now we may verify that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(A)=0.2+2\cdot0.1+0.1$
\end_inset

.
 Likewise,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(A^{C})=0.15+2\cdot0.15+0.05.$
\end_inset

 By symmetry and counting we find
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\pi_{1} & = & \pi_{2}=\pi_{3}=0.5,\\
\pi_{12} & = & \pi_{13}=\pi_{23}=0.2,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

so the mechanism is uniform PMCAR.
 However,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{123}(A)=0.1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{123}(A^{C})=0.05$
\end_inset

,
 so the mechanism is not MCAR.
 In fact,
 it is not even MAR,
 as the missingness mechanism depends probabilistically on 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\star}$
\end_inset

.
